{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608762/1958051101/0875.xml":{"full_text":"TODAY IN MCDICINC\nSurgery Fear Called\nObstacle to Recovery\nBy CHARLES G. BROOKS\nRur Staff Wrilar\nPear reactions, from mild apprehension to extreme p\u00bbnhn\nala. often can prevent complete recovery from surgery, par\nticularly among children.\nDespite this, there are many hospitals In which parents\nare either forbidden or discouraged from making visits to\ntheir children.\nThis Is a viewpoint expressed In the current Issue of OP,\nthe monthly journal of the\nAmerican Academy of Oeneral\nPractice. The article was writ\nten by Dr. Norman Chlvers and\nDr. Theodore L. Dorpat of the\nUniversity of Washington\nSchool of Medicine, Seattle\nTo the child the hospital Is\na strange, new world where un\ntold numbers of cloudy dangers\nlurk.\nChildren, the authors say,\noften feel that operations are\nforms of punishment. Some\ntimes even adults, subcon\nsciously, feel this way.\nFear of Death Is Factor\nThe ever-present fear of\ndeath plays an Important role\nIn emotional reactions which\ncan Influence the outcome of\nsurgery.\nCertain organs have a high\nsymbolic life-and-death signif\nicance. The outstanding ex\nample Is the heart. The phy\nsicians say a high proportion\nof patients facing heart opera\ntions show emergency defenses\nof Immobilisation, hysterical\namnesia, excitement or even\nBlood Center\nLists Output\nThe Washington Regional\nBlood Center last week dis\ntributed 1,847 pints of blood in\nthe District and the communi\nties covered by bloodmobiles in\nMaryland, Virginia and West\nVirginia\nThe District received 834\npints: Maryland. 378: Virginia,\nWest Virginia, 88. and 100 out\nside the area.\nIn addition to the weekly\nbloodmobile schedule, donors\nmay contribute at the'Wash\nington Hospital Center Blood\nBank. First street and Michi\ngan avenue N.W., 8 a m. to 4\np m.. Mondays through Fridays:\nFreedmen's Hospital. 9 a m to\n4:45 p.m. and 6 to 8 p m.. Mon\ndays through Fridays and 2 to\n5 pm. Sundays: Walter Reed\nHospital, 9 a m. to 4 p m.. Mon\ndays through Fridays and 7 to\n9 p.m.. Tuesdays: Washington\nRegional Blood Center, 1 to\n8:45 p.nV. Mondays, and 9 am.\nto 4:30 p.m., Tuesdays through\nFridays; Clinical Blood Center,\nNational Institutes of Health.\n8:30 a m. to 3:30 p.m.. Mondays\nthrough Fridays.\nBloodmobiles are scheduled\nto make the following visits this\nweek:\nMonday\u2014 Montgomery County Chap\nter. Atomic Energy Commission. Ger\nmantown. Md 9a m. to 3 p m Prince\nOeorges County Chapter. Medical Cen\nter. 7200 Marlboro pike. District\nHeights. Md 2 pm. to 8 pm.\nTuesday\u2014Charles County Chapter,\nNaval Powder Factory Indianhead.\nMd.. 8-30 am. to :t p.m. District of\nColumbia Chapter, yeterans\u2019 Adminis\ntration H street and Vermont avenue\nN.W Room No 200. 10 a m. to 4 p m.\nWednesday\u2014District of Columbia\nChapter. Pentacon, Room 4 A 750. 9:45\nam. to :i:.10 p m District of Colum\nbia Chapter Main Navy, Constitution\navenue at Eistheenth street. Room\n7541. 9:30 am to 3 pm District of\nColumbia Chapter. Anacostla National\nBank. 3850 South Capitol street at\nIntersection of Nichols avenue. D. C..\n10 a m. to 4 p.m.\nThursday\u2014Fairfax County Chapter,\nFort Belvoir. Va Old Hospital Build\ning 9:30 am. to 3:30 pm Clarke\nCounty Chapter. Community Building\nBerryville. Va., 10 a m to 4 p m (EBT-\nFriday\u2014Caroline County Chapter\nTown Hall. Bowling Green. Va 10\nam. to 4 p m (ESTI. Shepherdstown\nCountv Chapter, Men\u2019s Club Building,\nflhepherdstown. W. Va., 10 am. to\n4 p.m (DBT\u00bb.\n*tru z a V ,1, ,J s J,1 J* ,r,n A S\u2019*fr 1\nw u\n\u25a0Mil 1\n/V m i c A\n,CUiC? IMS'//J'it\nPEACE \u2018139.50\n;r FMrF.sEwiNG machine\nPLUG' 1 'j i\nfM rr\nl f\"\nJust MMt (be number if times tbe werd PFAFF appears iu\nt this ad. Enter your count to win one of these wonderful prizes. V\n'leawt But hurry...time is important! The earliest entry with the\nXt correct answe